The Bronx and Queens lawmaker, 33, is ‚Äúnot planning‚Äù to try to unseat Gillibrand, her campaign spokeswoman told The Post on Monday. Rep. Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez has backed off a potential Democratic primary challenge to Sen. Kirsten Gillibrand in 2024 ‚Äî just one month after refusing to rule out the possibility.

The Bronx and Queens lawmaker, 33, is ‚Äúnot planning‚Äù to try to unseat Gillibrand, her campaign spokeswoman told The Post on Monday.

With the field apparently clear of significant intra-party challengers, the 56-year-old Gillibrand has banked endorsements from key Democratic-supporting interest groups.

title: AOC Speaks Out on Potential TikTok Ban in Her First Post on the App
details: ICYMI: Rep. Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez has officially joined TikTok. In her first video posted to the platform, AOC spoke out against a potential ban on TikTok in the U.S., saying such action 'just doesn't feel right to me.' 'I think it‚Äôs important to discuss how unprecedented of a move this would be. The United States has never before banned a social media company from existence, from operating in our borders,' AOC said. 'And this is an app that has over 150 million Americans on it.' '[T]he United States is one of the only developed nations in the world that has no significant data or privacy protection laws on the books,' she continued. 'So to me, the solution here is not to ban an individual company ‚Äî but to actually protect Americans from this kind of egregious data harvesting that companies can do without your significant ability to say no.' text:
ICYMI: Rep. Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez has officially joined TikTok. In her first video posted to the platform, AOC spoke out against a potential ban on TikTok in the U.S., saying such action 'just doesn't feel right to me.'

'I think it‚Äôs important to discuss how unprecedented of a move this would be. The United States has never before banned a social media company from existence, from operating in our borders,' AOC said. 'And this is an app that has over 150 million Americans on it.'

'[T]he United States is one of the only developed nations in the world that has no significant data or privacy protection laws on the books,' she continued. 'So to me, the solution here is not to ban an individual company ‚Äî but to actually protect Americans from this kind of egregious data harvesting that companies can do without your significant ability to say no.'

As of March 27, AOC's TikTok has more than 3.5M views.

title: Gosar Censured Over AOC Murder Video, As AOC Slams GOP: What Is So Hard About Saying This Is Wrong?
details: Republican Congressmember Paul Gosar is the first lawmaker to be censured in more than a decade for posting an animated video on social media where he murders Congressmember Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and attacks President Biden. The U.S. House of Representatives also voted Tuesday to censure Gosar and strip him of committee assignments. He has refused to apologize and after the vote he retweeted the video. Speaking from the House floor before the vote Congressmember Ocasio-Cortez said: ‚ÄúThis is not about me. This is not about Representative Gosar. This is about what we are willing to accept.‚Äù The co-sponsor of the censure vote, Congressmember Jackie Speier of California, said ‚ÄúCongressmember Ocasio-Cortez has become the go-to subject of the radical right to stir up their base, as too often is the case for women of color.‚Äù #DemocracyNow Democracy Now! is an independent global news hour that airs on nearly 1,400 TV and radio stations Monday through Friday. Chris Wallace: Do people want both parties to move from the fringes, from the extremes back to the center?

Rep. Ocasio-Cortez: I think a lot of people in this country may say yes, but it‚Äôs important for us to dig into the substance of what that actually means. As someone who is often, I think, characterized as extreme. I of course, would object to that I do not believe that I am as extreme in the way that Marjorie Taylor Greene on the Republican side is extreme the idea that there is an equating of believing in someone who believes in guaranteed universal health care in the United States was someone who believes that undocumented people should incur physical harm are somehow in the same level of extreme is something that I would object to."

title: AOC Reacts To Republican Saying She Should "Educate Herself"
details: Republican Jeff Duncan said Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez should educate herself about fossil fuel extraction and she responded in kind. John Iadarola, Cenk Uygur, and Farron Cousins discuss on The Young Turks. Watch TYT LIVE on weekdays 6-8 pm ET. http://youtube.com/theyoungturks/live Read more HERE: https://www.newsweek.com/video-alexan... "A video of Republican congressman Jeff Duncan telling Democrat Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez to "educate yourself" has gone viral on social media, where it has collected over 3.2 million views. Duncan made the remark during a debate on the House floor over a bill asking the federal government "to approve a plan to increase drilling on federal lands and waters prior to any nonemergency drawdown" from the Strategic Petroleum Reserve [SPR] in non-emergency cases, as reported by Roll Call. The bill would require an increase in the percentage of public lands and offshore waters leased to match any drawdown from the SPR. Ocasio-Cortez proposed an amendment to the bill, introduced by House Energy and Commerce Chairwoman Cathy McMorris Rodgers on Thursday, arguing that leasing more land to fossil fuel companies would "guarantee that we will accelerate the devastating impact of climate change" and bring more profits to companies while not guaranteeing a drop in gas prices." *** The largest online progressive news show in the world. title: 'That Is Stunning': CNN Host Goes Quiet As AOC Says Ignore Court Ruling | The Kyle Kulinski Show
details: Support The Show On Patreon!: https://www.patreon.com/seculartalk Subscribe to Krystal Kyle & Friends On Substack!: https://krystalkyleandfriends.substac... Follow Kyle on Twitter: http://www.twitter.com/kylekulinski "The first time I ever really listened to Kyle Kulinski‚Äôs show was in the back of a cab last summer. The driver had his phone hooked up through the stereo and was pumping out an episode through the car speakers ‚Äî loudly, as if looking to convert a captive audience. ‚ÄúDo you like Kyle Kulinski?‚Äù The driver, Ahmed, was a recent immigrant and apparently a die-hard fan of Secular Talk, the political talk show that Kulinski broadcasts on YouTube. I told him, yes, in fact. I do like Kulinski, had come across his show several years ago, and, all things considered, he seemed pretty good. ‚ÄúHe understands what we‚Äôre up against,‚Äù Ahmed said. ‚ÄúLike Bernie.‚Äù But I was surprised to hear Kulinski‚Äôs name mentioned in the same breath as Bernie Sanders, particularly with such adoration. Because what I did remember about Kulinski‚Äôs show struck me as mostly capital-P ‚Äúprogressive‚Äù takes on the news ‚Äî the left wing of the Netroots crowd more than the democratic socialism Sanders has popularized. It‚Äôs an impression that wasn‚Äôt entirely incorrect. ‚ÄúI have no time for philosophical, airy bullshit,‚Äù Kulinski tells me from his home in Westchester, New York. ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt want to hear about Lenin. I don‚Äôt want to hear about Marx. I just want a super plainspoken, straightforward agenda with a straightforward way of selling it.‚Äù With over 800,000 subscribers and nearly 670 million total views on YouTube, selling a progressive agenda is clearly something Kulinski knows how to do ‚Äî even Democracy Now, the long-standing flagship of progressive media, cannot match his reach on the platform. Chapo Trap House can certainly boast a wildly devoted fan base (and a not insignificant degree of media influence), but their audience is roughly half the size of Kulinski‚Äôs. While Secular Talk might be more likely to be looped in with the progressive networks around Air America and Pacifica alums like Sam Seder than the more resolutely socialist world, Kulinski‚Äôs fiery rhetoric, razor-sharp class instincts, and knack for withering takedowns sets him apart from his peers. Judging by his rhetoric alone, he‚Äôs closer to a Eugene Debs than a Chris Hayes. But unlike Hayes, Amy Goodman, or his friend Cenk Uygur of The Young Turks ‚Äî who began airing Secular Talk on his web network seven years ago ‚Äî the thirty-two-year-old Kulinski is virtually invisible in the mainstream media. Despite his enormous fan base, his show has never once been mentioned in the obligatory trend pieces on ‚Äúthe Millennial Left‚Äù pumped out by the prestige media. Nor has Kulinski‚Äôs name ever popped up at all in the New York Times, Vox, the New Yorker, New York Magazine, or the Washington Post, despite his leading role in cofounding Justice Democrats, the organization widely credited with sweeping Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and the rest of ‚Äúthe Squad‚Äù to power. Just last week, his Wikipedia page was deleted. The reason? ‚ÄúThere is very simply no [reliable source] coverage of this person,‚Äù according to one moderator. In new media, he‚Äôs king ‚Äî the Sean Hannity of the Berniecrat left. In old media, he‚Äôs nobody. I suspect there are a few reasons for that. There is nothing ‚Äúcool‚Äù about Kulinski‚Äôs show. (As a friend put it, ‚Äú‚ÄòWelcome to Secular Talk‚Äô sounds like something you‚Äôd hear on Egyptian radio.‚Äù) His no-nonsense social-democratic politics won‚Äôt get him much cred with the Full Communism crowd. He records his show not in Brooklyn or Los Angeles, but in a studio he built himself in his modest Westchester home. His hair is too groomed and his taste in clothes too preppy to qualify as ‚ÄúDirtbag Left.‚Äù Nor has he ever attended an n+1 release party. ‚ÄúNot only have I not attended one,‚Äù he says, ‚ÄúI have no idea what that means.‚Äù And yet he‚Äôs astonishingly plugged-in for a young man in the suburbs. Wondering how Sanders ended up on the Joe Rogan Experience? Kulinski, a frequent guest on Rogan‚Äôs wildly popular show, introduced them. ‚ÄúYou make the most sense to me,‚Äù Rogan told Kulinski on a recent episode. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre a normal person.‚Äù Much like Sanders himself, Kulinski‚Äôs show has a massive audience that just doesn‚Äôt compute with our media‚Äôs understanding of ‚Äúwhat the kids want‚Äù or even ‚Äúwhat the left-wing kids want.‚Äù It‚Äôs probably for the best ‚Äî the very woke and very WASP-ish decorum haunting much of the media world is nowhere to be found in Secular Talk. ‚ÄúCorporate Democrats over-focus on identity as a trick to divert you from the issues that unite us all ‚Äî class issues,‚Äù he said on a recent episode. "The first time I ever really listened to Kyle Kulinski‚Äôs show was in the back of a cab last summer. The driver had his phone hooked up through the stereo and was pumping out an episode through the car speakers ‚Äî loudly, as if looking to convert a captive audience.

‚ÄúDo you like Kyle Kulinski?‚Äù

The driver, Ahmed, was a recent immigrant and apparently a die-hard fan of Secular Talk, the political talk show that Kulinski broadcasts on YouTube. I told him, yes, in fact. I do like Kulinski, had come across his show several years ago, and, all things considered, he seemed pretty good.

‚ÄúHe understands what we‚Äôre up against,‚Äù Ahmed said. ‚ÄúLike Bernie.‚Äù

But I was surprised to hear Kulinski‚Äôs name mentioned in the same breath as Bernie Sanders, particularly with such adoration. Because what I did remember about Kulinski‚Äôs show struck me as mostly capital-P ‚Äúprogressive‚Äù takes on the news ‚Äî the left wing of the Netroots crowd more than the democratic socialism Sanders has popularized.

It‚Äôs an impression that wasn‚Äôt entirely incorrect.

‚ÄúI have no time for philosophical, airy bullshit,‚Äù Kulinski tells me from his home in Westchester, New York. ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt want to hear about Lenin. I don‚Äôt want to hear about Marx. I just want a super plainspoken, straightforward agenda with a straightforward way of selling it.‚Äù

With over 800,000 subscribers and nearly 670 million total views on YouTube, selling a progressive agenda is clearly something Kulinski knows how to do ‚Äî even Democracy Now, the long-standing flagship of progressive media, cannot match his reach on the platform. Chapo Trap House can certainly boast a wildly devoted fan base (and a not insignificant degree of media influence), but their audience is roughly half the size of Kulinski‚Äôs.

While Secular Talk might be more likely to be looped in with the progressive networks around Air America and Pacifica alums like Sam Seder than the more resolutely socialist world, Kulinski‚Äôs fiery rhetoric, razor-sharp class instincts, and knack for withering takedowns sets him apart from his peers. Judging by his rhetoric alone, he‚Äôs closer to a Eugene Debs than a Chris Hayes.

But unlike Hayes, Amy Goodman, or his friend Cenk Uygur of The Young Turks ‚Äî who began airing Secular Talk on his web network seven years ago ‚Äî the thirty-two-year-old Kulinski is virtually invisible in the mainstream media. Despite his enormous fan base, his show has never once been mentioned in the obligatory trend pieces on ‚Äúthe Millennial Left‚Äù pumped out by the prestige media. Nor has Kulinski‚Äôs name ever popped up at all in the New York Times, Vox, the New Yorker, New York Magazine, or the Washington Post, despite his leading role in cofounding Justice Democrats, the organization widely credited with sweeping Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and the rest of ‚Äúthe Squad‚Äù to power.

Just last week, his Wikipedia page was deleted. The reason? ‚ÄúThere is very simply no [reliable source] coverage of this person,‚Äù according to one moderator. In new media, he‚Äôs king ‚Äî the Sean Hannity of the Berniecrat left. In old media, he‚Äôs nobody.

I suspect there are a few reasons for that. There is nothing ‚Äúcool‚Äù about Kulinski‚Äôs show. (As a friend put it, ‚Äú‚ÄòWelcome to Secular Talk‚Äô sounds like something you‚Äôd hear on Egyptian radio.‚Äù) His no-nonsense social-democratic politics won‚Äôt get him much cred with the Full Communism crowd. He records his show not in Brooklyn or Los Angeles, but in a studio he built himself in his modest Westchester home. His hair is too groomed and his taste in clothes too preppy to qualify as ‚ÄúDirtbag Left.‚Äù Nor has he ever attended an n+1 release party. ‚ÄúNot only have I not attended one,‚Äù he says, ‚ÄúI have no idea what that means.‚Äù

And yet he‚Äôs astonishingly plugged-in for a young man in the suburbs. Wondering how Sanders ended up on the Joe Rogan Experience? Kulinski, a frequent guest on Rogan‚Äôs wildly popular show, introduced them. ‚ÄúYou make the most sense to me,‚Äù Rogan told Kulinski on a recent episode. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre a normal person.‚Äù

Much like Sanders himself, Kulinski‚Äôs show has a massive audience that just doesn‚Äôt compute with our media‚Äôs understanding of ‚Äúwhat the kids want‚Äù or even ‚Äúwhat the left-wing kids want.‚Äù

It‚Äôs probably for the best ‚Äî the very woke and very WASP-ish decorum haunting much of the media world is nowhere to be found in Secular Talk. ‚ÄúCorporate Democrats over-focus on identity as a trick to divert you from the issues that unite us all ‚Äî class issues,‚Äù he said on a recent episode.

title: AOC Calls For Impeachment Of Justice Clarence Thomas
channelName: The Majority Report w/ Sam Seder
details: In a recent interview with Lever News's David Sirota, Rep. Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez (D-NY) called for the impeachment of US Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas. Ocasio-Cortez cited a recent ProPublica report that revealed Thomas accepted luxury travel and other gifts from a Republican megadonor, as well as Thomas's wife's involvement in efforts to overturn the 2020 election, as reasons for his impeachment. "This degree of corruption is shocking ‚Äî almost cartoonish," Ocasio-Cortez said. "Thomas must be impeached." Ocasio-Cortez is the first sitting member of Congress to call for Thomas's impeachment. It is unclear whether there is enough support in the House to impeach Thomas, but Ocasio-Cortez's call is likely to put pressure on Democrats to take action. text:
In a recent interview with Lever News's David Sirota, Rep. Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez (D-NY) called for the impeachment of US Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas. Ocasio-Cortez cited a recent ProPublica report that revealed Thomas accepted luxury travel and other gifts from a Republican megadonor, as well as Thomas's wife's involvement in efforts to overturn the 2020 election, as reasons for his impeachment.

"This degree of corruption is shocking ‚Äî almost cartoonish," Ocasio-Cortez said. "Thomas must be impeached."
Ocasio-Cortez is the first sitting member of Congress to call for Thomas's impeachment. It is unclear whether there is enough support in the House to impeach Thomas, but Ocasio-Cortez's call is likely to put pressure on Democrats to take action.

title: Adam Carolla Shocks Hannity With Disgusting AOC Attack
details: Fox News guest Adam Carolla harshly criticized Rep. Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez by claiming that the only reason people care about her is because she's a young attractive woman. Surprisingly, Sean Hannity didn't fully agree and engage with Carolla's statement, but both still agreed that her policy opinions are horrible. Cenk Uygur, John Iadarola, and Adrienne Lawrence discuss on The Young Turks. Watch LIVE weekdays 6-8 pm ET. http://youtube.com/theyoungturks/live Read more HERE: https://www.mediamatters.org/fox-news... "ADAM CAROLLA (GUEST): Here's a quick thought experiment: if AOC was fat and in her 60s, would anyone listen to another thing she ever said? SEAN HANNITY (HOST): Oh, boy. You're going to step in that one. What do you -- what exactly do you mean by that? You mean, is it because she's young and -- what? CAROLLA: Yes, she's young, she's vibrant, she's beautiful, and everyone's always putting a camera and a mic in her face. But her opinions are idiotic 95 percent of the time. And I don't think, if she was a middle-aged heavyset woman, anyone would care what she had to say. HANNITY: I'm not so sure I agree. Now, I will say this: you can criticize her ideas -- and I do, I think the Green New Deal is madness and insanity -- but she's got the whole Democratic Party following her. In my opinion, she's way more powerful than Speaker Pelosi. And if she and the squad decide Speaker Pelosi's out, I think she could probably be speaker. If she challenges Chuck Schumer in New York, I think she has a good shot at beating him. Maybe I'm wrong. CAROLLA: Look, I agree with you. title: Rep. AOC on Gun Reform After Buffalo, Uvalde Shootings
details: On June 8th, 2022, following testimony from victims of the Buffalo and Uvalde shootings, Rep. Ocasio-Cortez spoke on gun reform. Every week in recent memory, we have had at least one mass shooting ‚Äî and this is not normal. Between 2009 and 2018, the United States had 288 school shootings, while all other G7 countries combined had five. The way that we regulate guns in our country is deeply broken. And yet, the gun industry is doing everything it can to block gun reform. Gun companies make millions of dollars in profits, and then pour those profits directly into lobbying against firearm regulation. The House is expected to pass the Protecting Our Kids Act later today to address the gun violence epidemic. The legislation will then head to the Senate, where negotiations are occurring in an attempt to pass some form of gun control legislation. Republicans like to blame mental health as the cause of gun violence, yet are doing nothing to address the root causes of such violence. In addition to enacting gun control legislation, we also need to address the emergence of white supremacy radicalization, misogyny, domestic violence, mass incarceration, and poverty ‚Äî which are all connected to the mass shootings in our communities. #EndGunViolence
text:
On June 8th, 2022, following testimony from victims of the Buffalo and Uvalde shootings, Rep. Ocasio-Cortez spoke on gun reform.

Every week in recent memory, we have had at least one mass shooting ‚Äî and this is not normal. Between 2009 and 2018, the United States had 288 school shootings, while all other G7 countries combined had five.

The way that we regulate guns in our country is deeply broken. And yet, the gun industry is doing everything it can to block gun reform. Gun companies make millions of dollars in profits, and then pour those profits directly into lobbying against firearm regulation.

The House is expected to pass the Protecting Our Kids Act later today to address the gun violence epidemic. The legislation will then head to the Senate, where negotiations are occurring in an attempt to pass some form of gun control legislation.

Republicans like to blame mental health as the cause of gun violence, yet are doing nothing to address the root causes of such violence. In addition to enacting gun control legislation, we also need to address the emergence of white supremacy radicalization, misogyny, domestic violence, mass incarceration, and poverty ‚Äî which are all connected to the mass shootings in our communities. #EndGunViolence
